          "title": "Jesus the great high priest — sympathy without sin (4:14-15)",
          "body": "Verse 14 is the structural hinge of the entire epistle. The author has dropped hints (1:3 — \"He made purification for sins\"; 2:17 — \"a merciful and faithful high priest\"; 3:1 — \"consider Jesus, the apostle and high priest of our confession\"), but now he takes up the theme that will dominate chapters 5-10. Three claims pack the title. **Great** (megan) — superior in rank to all Aaronic predecessors. **Passed through the heavens** — where Aaron walked through curtains, Jesus walked through cosmic spheres into the true sanctuary. **Jesus the Son of God** — the human name and the divine title in one breath, the incarnational pivot of priestly mediation. Then verse 15 lands the pastoral payoff. Our high priest is not aloof; He *sympathizes* (sumpatheō — feels-with) our weaknesses because He has been *tempted in all things as we are* (kath' homoiotēta — \"according to likeness\"). And yet *without sin* — the qualification matters. His sympathy is not the camaraderie of a fellow failure but the perfect understanding of one who endured every temptation to the end. He knows what it costs to say no, because He paid the full cost."
